{
    "analysis": "The anomaly aggregation step computed global P95/P5 per (cmdb_id,kpi_name), filtered the 08:30–08:59 window, and marked anomalies. The top-20 anomalous pairs are dominated by two components: shippingservice2-0 (many container.node-5.* KPIs showing constant extreme values across the full 30-min window) and adservice (many runtime.java_lang_GarbageCollector_LastGcInfo_* KPIs showing extreme/constant values across the full window). These anomalies occur across every minute (anomaly_count=30) indicating persistent issues on those component-KPIs. No fault segmentation or trace/log correlation has been done yet, and we still need to (1) summarize which components have the most anomalous KPIs and their time ranges and (2) correlate with error_logs activity (to find the two distinct failure moments) before doing trace/log-based localization.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using cached kernel variables anomalies_df and error_logs_df, perform two compact aggregates and save results in kernel variables (return printed output compactly, max 20 rows each):\n1) Aggregate anomalies_df by cmdb_id: produce top 20 rows ordered by anomaly_count desc with columns: cmdb_id, anomaly_count, distinct_kpis (count of unique kpi_name), earliest_anomaly_ts, latest_anomaly_ts. Save as anomalies_by_component.\n2) From error_logs_df, filter to the incident window 2022-03-20 08:30:00+08:00 through 2022-03-20 08:59:59+08:00, then aggregate by minute (floor timestamps to minute if not already) and return top 20 minutes ordered by log_count desc with columns: minute_ts, log_count, top_cmdb_id (cmdb_id with highest logs at that minute), top_message_sample (most common message text for that minute). Save as error_logs_per_min.\nReturn both small tables in the Executor output (each limited to 20 rows)."
}

{
    "analysis": "From the previous trace and metric analyses: many metric anomalies span the entire 08:30–08:59 window and are concentrated on adservice/adservice2 (numerous JVM GC-related KPIs) and frontend pods (many anomalies and repeated warning logs 'failed to retrieve...'). Error logs peak at several minutes (08:33, 08:42, 08:48, 08:44) with frontends as the top cmdb_id, indicating repeated frontend failures contacting a downstream service (likely adservice). Trace-level anomalies were uninformative (many error_rate entries are constant zeros equal to thresholds). We still need to (1) determine the exact occurrence times of the two failures (pick the two distinct failure moments) and (2) for each failure, localize the root cause component and reason. To do that, we must confirm which component's metric faults began first and whether adservice/adservice2's JVM/GC-related anomalies temporally correlate with frontend error log spikes.

What remains: we need earliest anomaly timestamps and counts for GC/heap-related KPIs of adservice/adservice2 pods to see when those abnormalities began, and cross-check with the error-log minute spikes to map the two failures to the most likely root-cause component and time.

Therefore we will retrieve compact aggregates of metric anomalies focused on adservice/adservice2 (service and pods) for GC and memory related KPIs to get earliest anomaly timestamps, anomaly counts, and example extreme values. This will help decide the root cause component and exact occurrence times for the two failures.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From the cached anomalies_df, filter rows where cmdb_id is one of: ['adservice','adservice-0','adservice-1','adservice-2','adservice2','adservice2-0'] OR where cmdb_id starts with 'adservice' (case-sensitive), AND kpi_name contains any of the substrings: 'GarbageCollector', 'HeapMemory', 'Memory', 'LastGcInfo' (case-sensitive). Aggregate by cmdb_id and kpi_name and return up to 20 rows ordered by anomaly_count desc. For each row include: cmdb_id, kpi_name, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_ts, latest_anomaly_ts, min_value, max_value, p95, p5. Save the result as ad_gc_anomalies_df in kernel. Keep printed output compact (max 20 rows)." }

{
    "analysis": "We have computed global thresholds and marked anomalies for metrics and traces, and aggregated error logs by minute. Key observations so far: adservice and adservice2 show persistent GC/memory-related anomalies across the entire 08:30–08:59 window (anomaly_count=30, earliest 08:30). Frontend pods repeatedly emitted the same warning 'failed to retrieve...' with several peak minutes (08:33, 08:42, 08:48, 08:44, etc.) where log_count reached 20–21. Trace-level error_rate values are constant zeros and not helpful. We still need to map specific failure moments (two distinct failures) to the most likely root-cause components. To do that, we must correlate per-minute error-log peaks with which components had metric anomalies at those exact minutes — that will let us pick the two failure minutes and, for each, the most likely root-cause component and resource (from metrics) to explain the frontend errors.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From the cached metric_window_df (windowed metrics with is_anomaly flag) and error_logs_per_min, select the minutes where error_logs_per_min.log_count >= 20. For each such minute_ts, compute the count of metric anomaly rows grouped by cmdb_id for that exact minute (timestamp equality). Return a compact table with one row per minute containing: minute_ts, log_count, and up to top 3 components (cmdb_id and anomaly_count) ordered by anomaly_count desc for that minute. Limit output to all minutes with log_count >=20 (should be <=20 rows). Save the per-minute component-anomaly breakdown as minute_component_anomalies in the kernel for follow-up."
}

